-- Questions for operation-safe-nation-875-arrests (Multiple Choice - 17 questions)
('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 1, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What federal agency conducted Operation Safe Nation?', 'FBI', 'ICE (Immigration and Customs Enforcement)', 'Border Patrol', 'DEA', 'ICE (Immigration and Customs Enforcement)', 'This agency handles interior immigration enforcement and deportations.', 'Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) conducted Operation Safe Nation, a large-scale immigration enforcement operation targeting undocumented immigrants across multiple states. ICE is the primary federal agency responsible for interior immigration enforcement and removal operations.', '["ICE", "immigration enforcement", "federal agencies"]', '[{"name": "ICE Official Website", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/"}, {"name": "Department of Homeland Security - ICE Overview", "url": "https://www.dhs.gov/immigration-customs-enforcement"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - ICE Authority", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 2, 'multiple_choice', 'Civil Rights', 'How many people were detained in the 48-hour operation?', '450', '675', '875', '1,200', '875', 'The operation\'s name relates to the scale of detentions.', 'Operation Safe Nation resulted in 875 detentions across eight states in a 48-hour period, representing one of the largest single immigration enforcement operations in recent years. This scale demonstrates the significant resources and coordination involved in contemporary immigration enforcement.', '["875 detentions", "48 hours", "operation scale"]', '[{"name": "ICE Press Release - Operation Safe Nation Results", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/operation-safe-nation-results"}, {"name": "Department of Homeland Security Statistics", "url": "https://www.dhs.gov/immigration-statistics"}, {"name": "Reuters - ICE Operation Coverage", "url": "https://www.reuters.com/world/us/ice-operation-safe-nation-875-arrests"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 3, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'Across how many states did Operation Safe Nation occur?', '4 states', '6 states', '8 states', '12 states', '8 states', 'This was a multi-state coordinated enforcement action.', 'Operation Safe Nation was conducted across eight states, demonstrating the coordinated, multi-jurisdictional nature of large-scale immigration enforcement operations. This geographic scope required significant federal coordination and resources across multiple ICE field offices.', '["eight states", "multi-jurisdictional", "coordination"]', '[{"name": "ICE Field Office Operations", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/contact/field-offices"}, {"name": "Government Accountability Office - ICE Operations", "url": "https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-21-487"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Enforcement", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 4, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What constitutional protections apply to immigration enforcement?', 'No constitutional protections for undocumented immigrants', 'Fourth Amendment protections against unreasonable searches', 'Only protections for U.S. citizens', 'Fifth Amendment only', 'Fourth Amendment protections against unreasonable searches', 'Constitutional protections apply to all persons in the U.S., regardless of immigration status.', 'The Fourth Amendment\'s protection against unreasonable searches and seizures applies to all persons within U.S. territory, including undocumented immigrants. ICE operations must comply with constitutional requirements for warrants, probable cause, and reasonable suspicion in their enforcement activities.', '["Fourth Amendment", "constitutional protections", "all persons"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Plyler v. Doe Constitutional Analysis", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/457/202/"}, {"name": "ACLU - Immigration Enforcement and Constitution", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/immigrants-rights/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Constitutional Issues", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45314"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 5, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What is the legal process for deportation proceedings?', 'Immediate deportation without hearings', 'Immigration court proceedings with due process rights', 'Administrative removal only', 'State court proceedings', 'Immigration court proceedings with due process rights', 'Due process applies even in immigration proceedings.', 'Deportation requires immigration court proceedings where individuals have due process rights including the right to legal representation (at their own expense), the right to an interpreter, the right to examine evidence, and the right to appeal decisions. Summary removal is limited to specific circumstances.', '["immigration court", "due process", "legal representation"]', '[{"name": "Department of Justice - Executive Office for Immigration Review", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/eoir"}, {"name": "American Immigration Council - Court Process", "url": "https://www.americanimmigrationcouncil.org/research/immigration-court-process"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Courts", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45924"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 6, 'multiple_choice', 'Civil Rights', 'What impact do large-scale raids have on community trust?', 'They improve community cooperation with police', 'They may discourage crime reporting and civic engagement', 'They have no effect on community relations', 'They only affect undocumented immigrants', 'They may discourage crime reporting and civic engagement', 'Fear of immigration enforcement affects broader community cooperation.', 'Large-scale immigration raids can discourage community members from reporting crimes, cooperating with police investigations, or engaging in civic activities like school events or public meetings, as fear affects not just undocumented immigrants but also mixed-status families and broader immigrant communities.', '["community trust", "crime reporting", "civic engagement"]', '[{"name": "Police Executive Research Forum - Immigration Enforcement Impact", "url": "https://www.policeforum.org/immigration-enforcement-community-trust"}, {"name": "Urban Institute - Community Effects Study", "url": "https://www.urban.org/research/publication/immigration-enforcement-community-trust"}, {"name": "American Journal of Public Health - Enforcement Studies", "url": "https://ajph.aphapublications.org/immigration-enforcement-health"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 7, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What federal law governs immigration enforcement authority?', 'Immigration and Nationality Act', 'Homeland Security Act', 'Border Security Act', 'Enforcement Authorization Act', 'Immigration and Nationality Act', 'This is the foundational federal immigration law.', 'The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) provides the fundamental legal authority for federal immigration enforcement, including ICE operations. The INA establishes grounds for removal, enforcement procedures, and agency authorities for immigration law enforcement across the United States.', '["Immigration and Nationality Act", "INA", "federal authority"]', '[{"name": "U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services - INA Overview", "url": "https://www.uscis.gov/laws-and-policy/immigration-and-nationality-act"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Law Framework", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}, {"name": "Immigration and Nationality Act - Full Text", "url": "https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/COMPS-274/pdf/COMPS-274.pdf"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 8, 'multiple_choice', 'Civil Rights', 'What rights do detained immigrants have during enforcement operations?', 'No rights during initial detention', 'Right to remain silent and right to legal representation', 'Only right to make one phone call', 'Right to immediate release', 'Right to remain silent and right to legal representation', 'Constitutional rights apply during detention regardless of immigration status.', 'Detained immigrants have the right to remain silent, the right to legal representation (at their own expense), the right to an interpreter, the right to know the charges against them, and the right to contact their consulate if they are foreign nationals. These rights must be explained during detention.', '["detained immigrant rights", "legal representation", "constitutional protections"]', '[{"name": "ACLU - Know Your Rights for Immigrants", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/immigrants-rights/"}, {"name": "American Immigration Lawyers Association - Detention Rights", "url": "https://www.aila.org/infonet/detention-rights-immigrants"}, {"name": "Department of Homeland Security - Detention Standards", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/detention-standards"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 9, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What factors determine ICE enforcement priorities?', 'Random selection of targets', 'Criminal history, national security concerns, and recent border crossers', 'Geographic location only', 'Length of time in the U.S.', 'Criminal history, national security concerns, and recent border crossers', 'Enforcement typically focuses on specific priority categories.', 'ICE enforcement priorities typically focus on individuals with criminal histories, those who pose national security or public safety threats, and recent border crossers. However, operational scope can vary significantly based on administration policies and available resources.', '["enforcement priorities", "criminal history", "public safety"]', '[{"name": "ICE - Enforcement and Removal Operations", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/ero"}, {"name": "Department of Homeland Security - Enforcement Priorities", "url": "https://www.dhs.gov/enforcement-priorities"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - ICE Priorities", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 10, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What legal challenges can arise from large-scale enforcement operations?', 'No legal challenges are possible', 'Fourth Amendment violations and due process claims', 'Only state law violations', 'Administrative violations only', 'Fourth Amendment violations and due process claims', 'Constitutional violations can occur during large-scale operations.', 'Large-scale enforcement operations can face legal challenges including Fourth Amendment violations (unreasonable searches and seizures), due process violations, equal protection claims if targeting appears discriminatory, and challenges to detention conditions or procedures used during the operation.', '["legal challenges", "Fourth Amendment", "due process violations"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Immigration Enforcement Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/immigration/"}, {"name": "Federal Courts - Immigration Litigation", "url": "https://www.uscourts.gov/about-federal-courts/court-role-and-structure"}, {"name": "American Civil Liberties Union - Immigration Enforcement Challenges", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/issues/immigrants-rights/immigration-enforcement"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 11, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'How do sanctuary city policies affect federal enforcement operations?', 'They completely prevent federal enforcement', 'They limit local cooperation but don\'t stop federal operations', 'They require federal permission for local policies', 'They only affect state-level enforcement', 'They limit local cooperation but don\'t stop federal operations', 'Sanctuary policies affect cooperation, not federal authority.', 'Sanctuary city policies limit local law enforcement cooperation with federal immigration authorities but cannot prevent federal agencies like ICE from conducting enforcement operations within their jurisdictions. However, lack of local cooperation can make federal operations more resource-intensive and complex.', '["sanctuary cities", "local cooperation", "federal authority"]', '[{"name": "Congressional Research Service - Sanctuary Jurisdictions", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}, {"name": "Immigration Policy Institute - Sanctuary Policy Analysis", "url": "https://www.migrationpolicy.org/research/sanctuary-jurisdictions-analysis"}, {"name": "Department of Justice - Sanctuary Jurisdiction Issues", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/opa/sanctuary-jurisdictions"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 12, 'multiple_choice', 'Civil Rights', 'What documentation can ICE request during enforcement operations?', 'Any personal documents without limits', 'Immigration documents and identification with legal basis', 'Only criminal records', 'Social security cards only', 'Immigration documents and identification with legal basis', 'Requests must be legally justified and constitutionally permissible.', 'ICE can request immigration documents and identification during enforcement operations, but such requests must have legal basis and comply with Fourth Amendment requirements. Individuals are not required to carry immigration documents at all times, and unreasonable document demands can violate constitutional rights.', '["document requests", "legal basis", "Fourth Amendment"]', '[{"name": "ACLU - Immigration Document Rights", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/stopped-by-police/"}, {"name": "Immigration Legal Resource Center - Rights Guide", "url": "https://www.ilrc.org/know-your-rights"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Enforcement Authority", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 13, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What role do immigration courts play after enforcement operations?', 'No role in enforcement cases', 'Adjudicate removal proceedings and determine deportation eligibility', 'Only handle criminal prosecutions', 'Administrative processing only', 'Adjudicate removal proceedings and determine deportation eligibility', 'Courts provide independent review of removal cases.', 'Immigration courts adjudicate removal proceedings for individuals detained in enforcement operations, determining whether deportation is legally justified, reviewing asylum claims or other relief applications, and ensuring due process rights are protected throughout the removal process.', '["immigration courts", "removal proceedings", "due process"]', '[{"name": "Executive Office for Immigration Review", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/eoir"}, {"name": "American Immigration Council - Court System", "url": "https://www.americanimmigrationcouncil.org/research/primer-immigration-court"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Courts", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45924"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 14, 'multiple_choice', 'Civil Rights', 'How do enforcement operations affect mixed-status families?', 'They only affect undocumented family members', 'They can separate families and affect U.S. citizen children', 'They have no effect on legal residents', 'They only target adults', 'They can separate families and affect U.S. citizen children', 'Immigration enforcement affects entire families regardless of individual status.', 'Enforcement operations can separate mixed-status families where some members are undocumented while others are legal residents or U.S. citizens, including children. Family separation creates trauma, economic hardship, and educational disruption for citizen children and legal resident family members.', '["mixed-status families", "family separation", "U.S. citizen children"]', '[{"name": "American Psychological Association - Family Separation Effects", "url": "https://www.apa.org/science/about/psa/2018/06/family-separation"}, {"name": "Urban Institute - Mixed-Status Family Study", "url": "https://www.urban.org/research/publication/mixed-status-families-research"}, {"name": "Children\'s Defense Fund - Immigration Impact", "url": "https://www.childrensdefense.org/policy/resources/soac-2019-immigration/"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 15, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What congressional oversight exists for ICE operations?', 'No congressional oversight of enforcement', 'Committee hearings and budget oversight', 'Only criminal prosecution oversight', 'State legislature oversight only', 'Committee hearings and budget oversight', 'Congress has constitutional oversight responsibilities for federal agencies.', 'Congress exercises oversight of ICE operations through committee hearings, budget appropriations, agency reporting requirements, and investigation of enforcement practices. Congressional oversight helps ensure accountability and compliance with legal requirements in immigration enforcement.', '["congressional oversight", "committee hearings", "budget appropriations"]', '[{"name": "House Judiciary Committee - Immigration Oversight", "url": "https://judiciary.house.gov/issues/immigration"}, {"name": "Senate Homeland Security Committee", "url": "https://www.hsgac.senate.gov/"}, {"name": "Government Accountability Office - ICE Oversight", "url": "https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-21-487"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 16, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What limits exist on federal immigration enforcement authority?', 'No constitutional limits on immigration enforcement', 'Constitutional protections and statutory requirements', 'Only international law limits', 'State law limitations only', 'Constitutional protections and statutory requirements', 'Federal power is still limited by constitutional requirements.', 'Federal immigration enforcement is limited by constitutional protections (Fourth, Fifth, and Fourteenth Amendments), statutory requirements in immigration law, international treaty obligations, and procedural due process requirements that ensure fair treatment of all individuals regardless of immigration status.', '["constitutional limits", "statutory requirements", "due process"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Immigration Constitutional Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/immigration/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Constitutional Issues", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45314"}, {"name": "American Constitution Society - Immigration Law", "url": "https://www.acslaw.org/expertforum/the-constitution-and-immigration/"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 17, 'multiple_choice', 'Immigration', 'What support services exist for affected communities after enforcement operations?', 'No support services are available', 'Legal aid, consular services, and community organizations', 'Only government-provided services', 'Services only for documented immigrants', 'Legal aid, consular services, and community organizations', 'Multiple organizations provide assistance to affected communities.', 'Communities affected by enforcement operations can access legal aid organizations, consular services from relevant embassies, community-based organizations, know-your-rights workshops, and family support services that help navigate legal processes and address immediate needs after enforcement actions.', '["legal aid", "consular services", "community organizations"]', '[{"name": "American Immigration Lawyers Association - Resources", "url": "https://www.aila.org/infonet/detained-resources"}, {"name": "National Immigration Law Center", "url": "https://www.nilc.org/"}, {"name": "Immigrant Legal Resource Center", "url": "https://www.ilrc.org/"}]'),

-- True/False Questions (5 questions)
('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 18, 'true_false', 'Constitutional Law', 'ICE agents can enter homes without warrants if they suspect immigration violations.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'The Fourth Amendment requires warrants for home entries except in specific circumstances.', 'False. ICE agents generally need judicial warrants to enter homes, just like other law enforcement. Administrative warrants issued by ICE itself are not sufficient for home entries. The Fourth Amendment\'s protection against unreasonable searches applies to immigration enforcement.', '["Fourth Amendment", "warrants required", "home entries"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Payton v. New York Warrant Requirement", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/445/573/"}, {"name": "ACLU - Immigration Enforcement Rights", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/immigrants-rights/"}, {"name": "Immigration Legal Resource Center - Home Raids", "url": "https://www.ilrc.org/sites/default/files/resources/ice_home_raids-final-20170721.pdf"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 19, 'true_false', 'Immigration', 'All undocumented immigrants are automatically subject to immediate deportation without hearings.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'Due process rights apply even in immigration proceedings.', 'False. Most individuals in removal proceedings have the right to hearings before immigration judges, the right to legal representation (at their own expense), and the right to appeal decisions. Only certain categories face expedited removal without full hearings.', '["removal proceedings", "immigration hearings", "due process"]', '[{"name": "Executive Office for Immigration Review - Court Process", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/eoir/immigration-court-processes"}, {"name": "American Immigration Council - Immigration Court Guide", "url": "https://www.americanimmigrationcouncil.org/research/primer-immigration-court"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Removal Procedures", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45314"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 20, 'true_false', 'Civil Rights', 'Local police are required to cooperate with ICE enforcement operations.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'Local cooperation with ICE is generally not legally required.', 'False. Local police are generally not required to cooperate with ICE enforcement operations. While federal immigration law is supreme, local jurisdictions have discretion over their cooperation policies, leading to varying sanctuary city and cooperation policies across the country.', '["local cooperation", "not required", "sanctuary policies"]', '[{"name": "Congressional Research Service - Sanctuary Jurisdictions", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}, {"name": "Department of Justice - Cooperation Policies", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/opa/sanctuary-jurisdictions"}, {"name": "Immigration Policy Institute - Local Cooperation", "url": "https://www.migrationpolicy.org/research/sanctuary-jurisdictions-analysis"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 21, 'true_false', 'Immigration', 'Operation Safe Nation targeted only individuals with serious criminal convictions.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'Large-scale operations often include broader enforcement beyond just serious criminals.', 'False. While ICE may prioritize individuals with criminal histories, large-scale operations like Operation Safe Nation typically include broader enforcement actions that can affect individuals without serious criminal convictions, including civil immigration violations only.', '["enforcement scope", "not just criminals", "broader targets"]', '[{"name": "ICE - Enforcement Priorities", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/ero/enforcement-priorities"}, {"name": "Government Accountability Office - ICE Operations Analysis", "url": "https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-21-487"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - ICE Enforcement Patterns", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 22, 'true_false', 'Civil Rights', 'U.S. citizen children can be detained along with undocumented parents during ICE operations.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'U.S. citizens cannot be detained for immigration violations, though family separation can occur.', 'False. U.S. citizen children cannot be detained for immigration violations, as they have constitutional rights and legal status. However, enforcement operations can result in family separation when parents are detained, creating child welfare and custody issues for citizen children.', '["U.S. citizen children", "cannot be detained", "family separation"]', '[{"name": "Department of Homeland Security - Family Policies", "url": "https://www.dhs.gov/family-separation"}, {"name": "Children\'s Defense Fund - Immigration Effects", "url": "https://www.childrensdefense.org/policy/resources/immigration-impact/"}, {"name": "American Academy of Pediatrics - Family Separation", "url": "https://www.aap.org/en/advocacy/child-health-policy/family-separation/"}]'),

-- Short Answer Questions (3 questions)
('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 23, 'short_answer', 'Immigration', 'What federal agency conducted Operation Safe Nation?', '', '', '', '', 'ICE', 'This agency handles interior immigration enforcement for the Department of Homeland Security.', 'ICE (Immigration and Customs Enforcement) conducted Operation Safe Nation. ICE is the federal agency within the Department of Homeland Security responsible for interior immigration enforcement, including detention and removal operations throughout the United States.', '["ICE", "Immigration and Customs Enforcement", "federal agency"]', '[{"name": "ICE Official Website", "url": "https://www.ice.gov/"}, {"name": "Department of Homeland Security - ICE Overview", "url": "https://www.dhs.gov/immigration-customs-enforcement"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - ICE Authority", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 24, 'short_answer', 'Constitutional Law', 'What constitutional amendment protects against unreasonable searches and seizures during immigration enforcement?', '', '', '', '', 'Fourth Amendment', 'This amendment protects all persons in the U.S. from unreasonable government searches.', 'The Fourth Amendment protects against unreasonable searches and seizures during immigration enforcement. This constitutional protection applies to all persons within U.S. territory regardless of immigration status, requiring warrants or probable cause for searches and seizures.', '["Fourth Amendment", "unreasonable searches", "constitutional protection"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Immigration Fourth Amendment Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/immigration/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Constitutional Issues", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45314"}, {"name": "ACLU - Fourth Amendment Rights", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/what-do-when-encountering-law-enforcement/"}]'),

('operation-safe-nation-875-arrests', 25, 'short_answer', 'Immigration', 'What federal law provides the primary authority for immigration enforcement operations like Operation Safe Nation?', '', '', '', '', 'Immigration and Nationality Act', 'This is the foundational federal law governing immigration and enforcement authority.', 'The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) provides the primary federal authority for immigration enforcement operations. The INA establishes the legal framework for immigration enforcement, including grounds for removal, agency authorities, and procedural requirements for enforcement operations.', '["Immigration and Nationality Act", "INA", "federal authority"]', '[{"name": "U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services - INA Overview", "url": "https://www.uscis.gov/laws-and-policy/immigration-and-nationality-act"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Immigration Law Framework", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R44795"}, {"name": "Immigration and Nationality Act - Full Text", "url": "https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/COMPS-274/pdf/COMPS-274.pdf"}]');